  "prompt": "I'm 4 years into my H1B, my GC is not yet started. If I apply GC through consulting company, do I need to join this company before filing I-140/I485?",
  "response": "When applying for a Green Card (GC) through an employer while on an H-1B visa, the specifics can vary depending on the circumstances of your employment and the company's policies. Generally, here are some key points to consider:\n\n1. **Job Offer Requirement**: For the employer to sponsor your Green Card, you usually need to have a job offer from them. This means you should be employed with the consulting company at the time of filing the I-140 petition.\n\n2. **I-140 Petition**: The I-140 is a petition filed by your employer on your behalf. Typically, this petition is based on the premise that there is a permanent job offer available for you. Therefore, it is common for you to be employed by the sponsoring employer when the I-140 is filed.\n\n3. **I-485 Application**: The I-485 is the application to adjust your status to permanent resident. You can file the I-485 if your priority date is current and you are physically present in the U.S. However, your employment status with the sponsoring employer can be important, especially if you are relying on them for the job offer associated with your Green Card process.\n\n4. **Consulting Companies**: If you are looking to apply for a Green Card through a consulting company, it is crucial to ensure that the job you are being sponsored for is genuine and that you will be employed in that role. Consulting companies sometimes have specific arrangements regarding employment, so it is important to clarify these details with them.\n\n5. **Job Change Considerations**: If you are considering changing employers or are unsure about the employment arrangement, it is wise to consult with an immigration attorney. They can provide personalized advice based on your specific situation and help you navigate the process.\n\nIn summary, it is generally advisable to be employed with the consulting company before filing the I-140 petition. Always consult with an immigration attorney to understand the implications of your specific circumstances.",
